GLASS MOUNTAIN PIPELINE, LLC RULES, REGULATIONS, AND RATES
Governing the Interstate Transportation of CRUDE OIL BY PIPELINE
GENERAL APPLICATION
The Rules and Regulations published herein apply only under tariffs making specific reference by FERC number to this tariff: such references will include supplements hereto and successive issues hereof. Specific rules and regulations published in individual tariffs will take precedence over Rules and Regulations published herein.
The provisions published herein will, if effective, not result in an effect on the quality of the human environment.
Filed in compliance with [W] 18 C.F.R. § 342.2 (b) (Establishing Initial Rates) 18 C.F.R. § 342.3 (Indexing)

GENERAL RULES AND REGULATIONS 5. DEFINITIONS
· API – American Petroleum Institute.
· Barrel – forty two (42) United States gallons at sixty degrees (600) Fahrenheit.
· Carrier – Glass Mountain Pipeline, LLC
· [N] Committed Shipper - Any Shipper that makes a ship-or-pay commitment to Carrier via a transportation services agreement, for an effective date on or before December 31, 2026, of at least 12,000 BPD for an initial term of at least six (6) months from Alva, Oklahoma, to Cushing, Oklahoma.
· Crude Oil – the direct liquid product of oil wells, or the indirect liquid petroleum products of oil or gas wells, or a mixture of such products.
· Nomination – a written designation by a Shipper to Carrier of a stated quantity of Crude Oil for transportation from a specified origin point or points of Carrier to a specified destination point or points of Carrier over a period of one Operating Month in accordance with these Rules and Regulations.
· Operating Month – the month shall be deemed to begin the first day of such month at 0700 hours until the first day of the succeeding month at 0659 hours (Central Standard or Central Daylight Savings Time).
· Pipeline System – the pipeline in which Carrier or its affiliate owns an interest and which Carrier operates, and to which these rules and regulations are applicable.
· Shipper – a party who contracts with Carrier for transportation of Crude Oil, as defined under the terms of these rules and regulations.
· Tender – an offer by a Shipper to Carrier in accordance with these rules and regulations for the transportation of a stated quantity of Crude Oil from a specified origin of Carrier to specified destination point.
· [N] Uncommitted Shipper - Any Shipper that is not a Committed Shipper.
10. NOMINATIONS
Shippers desiring to tender Crude Oil shall provide Carrier with written notice of its Nomination. Crude Oil will be accepted for transportation hereunder as operations permit provided such Crude Oil is of similar quality and characteristics as is being transported from receipt point to destination point.
Any Shipper desiring to tender Crude Oil for transportation shall make a Nomination to the Carrier in writing by 5:00 p.m. (Central Time) on or before the 25th day on the month proceeding the month during which the transportation under the Nomination is to begin.
15. TITLE
Carrier shall have the right to reject any Crude Oil, when tendered for transportation, which may be involved in litigation, or the title of which may be in dispute, or which may be encumbered by a lien or charge of any kind, and it may require the Shipper to provide satisfactory evidence of its perfect and unencumbered title or satisfactory indemnity bond to protect Carrier. By tendering Crude Oil, Shipper warrants and guarantees that Shipper has good title thereto and agrees to hold Carrier harmless of any and all loss, cost, liability, damage and/or expense resulting from failure of title thereto. Acceptance of Crude Oil for transportation hereunder shall not be deemed an acknowledgment by Carrier as to title.
20. CONNECTION REQUIREMENTS
All proposed receiving or delivery connections must meet tender, tankage, hourly flow rate conditions, and metering requirements as they exist at the time of requested connection and must also have provision which will allow for increases to maximum line flow rate and pressure conditions. All proposed connection designs must be approved in advance in writing by Carrier, and all costs of connections shall be paid by the connecting party.
25. LINE FILL REQUIREMENTS
Shipper shall furnish required inventory prior to delivering barrels out of Carrier’s Pipeline System. Shipper will be required to supply a pro rata share of Crude Oil (adjusted quarterly based on each Shipper’s prior three months’ throughput) for efficient operation of Carrier’s pipeline. Shipper may withdraw its required line inventory of Crude Oil only after Shipper’s shipments have ceased and Shipper has notified Carrier in writing at least two months prior to the effective date of Shipper’s intention to discontinue shipments in Carrier’s system. Carrier is temporarily waiving the linefill requirement pursuant to this Item No. 25, and Carrier will supply the proportional share of linefill for such transportation services until further notice. Carrier will provide notice prior to the date Nominations are due for the following month if such waiver changes or is removed.
30. QUALITY SPECIFICATIONS
Carrier will reject all Tenders when: (1) the vapor pressure of the Crude Oil exceeds twelve pounds (12 lbs.) at one hundred degrees Fahrenheit (1000 F); (2) the true vapor pressure of the Crude Oil might results in Carrier’s non-compliance with federal, state, or local regulations; (3) the crude oil contains impurities exceeding one percent (1%) including not more than three-tenths percent (0.3%) water; (4) Minimum and Maximum API gravity and sulfur content of the Crude Oil received at the Alva, Oklahoma injection facilities are as follow:
Percent Sulfur Minimum and Maximum Gravity (API)
<= 0.75 28.1-40.0
and; (5) if Carrier determines that a Shipper has delivered to Carrier’s facilities Crude Oil that has been contaminated by the presences of any excess metals including but not limited to chlorinated and/or oxygenated hydrocarbons and salt, such Shipper will be excluded from further entry into the system until such time as quality specifications have been demonstrated by Shipper to be met. Any liability associated with the contamination or disposal of any Crude Oil shall be borne by responsible Shipper.
No Crude Oil will be accepted unless its gravity, viscosity, and other characteristics are such that it will be readily susceptible to transportation through Carrier’s existing facilities, and it will not materially and adversely affect the quality of Crude Oil from other Shippers or cause disadvantage to other Shippers or Carrier.
35. GAUGING, TESTING AND DEDUCTIONS
Crude Oil shipped hereunder shall be measured and tested by a representative of the Carrier or by automatic equipment approved by Carrier. Quantities shall be determined by dynamic or static measurement methods in accordance with appropriate API standards, latest revision, and adjusted to base (reference or standard) conditions. Corrections will be made for temperature from observed degrees Fahrenheit to 60 degrees Fahrenheit and the full percentage of water or other impurities as ascertained by a centrifuge machine or other tests will be deducted from the corrected volume.
Shipper or its representative shall have the privilege of being present or represented during the gauging or metering and testing performed by Carrier. Shipper shall grant access to Shipper’s facility to Carrier’s representative and to any connecting carrier’s representative for witnessing meter or gauge readings or meter proving and for any other required inspection incidental to measurement and transportation of Crude Oil.
[C] Any shortage, including losses resulting from shrinkage, evaporation, other physical loss and interface mixture in any calendar month, will be allocated on a monthly accrual basis among Shippers in the proportion that the total number of Barrels delivered from the entire system, or applicable pipeline segment, for each Shipper bears to the total number of Barrels delivered from the entire system, or applicable pipeline segment, for all Shippers. Consignee shall be entitled to receive only that portion of a Shipper’s shipment remaining after adjusting for said Shipper’s proportion of such shortage, determined as aforesaid.
[N] All receipts of Crude Oil shall be subject to a deduction of two-tenths of one percent (0.2%) to cover line loss due to shrinkage and evaporation.
40. DESTINATION FACILITIES REQUIRED
Carrier will accept Crude Oil for transportation only when the Shipper has made the necessary arrangements for shipment beyond or has provided the necessary facilities for receiving said Crude Oil as it arrives at the destination.
45. DELIVERIES AND DEMURRAGE
The obligation of Carrier is to deliver the quantity of Crude Oil to be transported, less deductions noted in Item No. 35 above, at the specified destination. Such delivery may be made upon twenty-four (24) hours’ notice to Shipper who shall accept and receive said Crude Oil from Carrier with all possible dispatch into tanks arranged for by Shipper. After the first seven o’clock a.m. notice after expiration of said 24-hour notice, Carrier shall assess a demurrage charge on any part of said Crude Oil tendered for delivery and remaining undelivered, at the rate for each day of twenty-four (24) hours, or fractional part thereof, at [U]55.00 cents per barrel per day.
50. MIXING IN TRANSIT
Crude Oil will be accepted for transportation only on condition that it shall be subject to normal changes in general characteristics while in transit as may result from the mixture of such Crude Oil with other similar Crude Oil in the pipeline and/or tanks of Carrier or connecting carrier. Carrier will not be liable for variations of gravity or quality of Crude Oil occurring while in its custody and is under no obligation to deliver the identical Crude Oil as received. There shall be no adjustment for downgrading or upgrading of Crude Oil tendered for transportation as a result of mixing in transit.
55. APPLICATION OF RATES AND CHARGES
Crude Oil accepted for transportation shall be subject to the rates and charges in effect on the date of receipt by Carrier. Transportation and all other lawful charges will be collected on the basis of net quantities of Crude Oil delivered as determined in the manner provided in Item No. 35.
60. PAYMENT OF TRANSPORTATION AND OTHER CHARGES
Shipper shall be responsible for payment of transportation and all other charges applicable to the shipment and, at the discretion of Carrier, may be required to pre-pay such charges or furnish guaranty of payment satisfactory to Carrier. Payments not received by Carrier within fifteen (15) days of date of invoice terms shall be subject to a late charge equivalent to 125% of the prime rate as quoted in The Wall Street Journal. Carrier shall have, and Shipper hereby grants, a lien on all Crude Oil accepted for transportation to cover payment of all charges, including demurrage, legal fees, and late charges and may refuse to make delivery of Crude Oil until all charges have been paid. If the Crude Oil remains in the custody of the Carrier for more than thirty (30) days after the tender of delivery by Carrier, Carrier shall have the right to sell the Crude Oil at a public or private sale in a commercially reasonable manner to collect such charges. Carrier reserves the right to set-off any charges against any monies owed to Shipper by Carrier, or any Crude Oil of Shipper in Carrier’s custody.
65. LIABILITY OF CARRIER
Carrier shall not, while in possession of Crude Oil, be liable for any loss of Crude Oil, damage thereto, or delay because of any act of God, the public enemy, civil disorder, quarantine, the authority of the laws, strikes, riots, fire, floods or the acts of default of Shipper, or from any other force majeure event or similar causes not due to the sole negligence of Carrier. In case of loss of Crude Oil for which Carrier is not responsible, the Shipper shall bear all costs. When such loss occurs in the System which is the property of more than one Shipper (tank or line batch) each Shipper shall bear the loss in such proportion as its volume in said tank or batch bears to the total volume in said tank or batch. Carrier will be obligated to deliver only that portion of a Crude Oil shipment remaining after deducting such loss. Transportation charges shall only be applied on quantities of Crude Oil delivered.
70. WARRANTIES
Shipper warrants that the Crude Oil tendered to Carrier will conform to the specifications stated in Item No. 30, will be merchantable, and will not be contaminated. Shipper will be liable to Carrier and/or other shippers for any damage, including special, incidental, and consequential, arising from a breach of this warranty. The transportation of the Crude Oil will be refused or canceled if Carrier determines or is advised that the Crude Oil does not meet the requirements of these Rules and Regulations.
75. DUTY OF CARRIER
Carrier shall not be required to transport Crude Oil except with reasonable diligence, considering the quality of the Crude Oil, the distance of transportation and other material elements. Carrier cannot commit to delivering Crude Oil to a particular destination, at a particular time.
80. CLAIMS AND TIME FOR FILING
As a condition precedent to recovery for loss, damage, or delay of shipments, claims must be filed in writing with the Carrier within nine (9) months after the delivery of the Crude Oil, or, in case of failure to make delivery, then within nine (9) months after a reasonable time for delivery has elapsed. Suits arising out of such claims must be instituted against Carrier only within two (2) years from the time when the Carrier delivers, or tenders delivery of the Crude Oil or, in case of failure to make or tender delivery, then within two (2) years after a reasonable time for delivery has elapsed. Where claims are not filed or suits are not instituted thereon in accordance with the foregoing provisions, Carrier will not be liable and such claims will not be paid.
85. ADDITIVES
Carrier reserves the right to require, approve or reject the injection of corrosion inhibitors, viscosity or pour point depressants, drag reducing agent, or other such additives in Crude Oil to be transported.
90. PRORATION OF PIPELINE CAPACITY
Definitions utilized for this Item 90 are as follows:
Available Capacity – the total available capacity on the Pipeline System during a calendar month.
Base Period – a period of 12 consecutive months, excluding the month prior to Pipeline System proration.
Base Shipment Percentage – means, for each Regular Shipper, the total deliveries of Crude Oil by the Regular Shipper during the Base Period divided by the total deliveries of Crude Oil on the Pipeline System during the Base Period.
New Shipper – a Shipper that is not a Regular Shipper.
Proration Month – means the calendar month for which capacity is being prorated. Regular Shipper – a Shipper that has shipments in at least six months of the Base Period. If the total volume of Crude Oil nominated is in excess of the Available Capacity, Crude Oil will be apportioned for acceptance and transportation on the Pipeline System in the following manner:
1. Available Capacity shall be divided between New Shippers as a class and Regular Shippers as a class.
2. Up to 10 percent of the Available Capacity shall be made available to New Shippers during a Proration Month. Each New Shipper shall be allocated an amount of capacity during a Proration Month that is equal to its Nomination; provided, however, that if the total Nominations by New Shippers exceed 10 percent of the Available Capacity, then each New Shipper’s allocation will be reduced on a pro rata basis, in accordance with its Nomination, so that the allocation to all New Shippers in the aggregate does not exceed 10 percent of the Available Capacity.
3. After the allocation of capacity to New Shipper, all remaining Available Capacity shall be allocated among all Regular Shippers in proportion to their Base Shipment Percentages. In the event the capacity that would be allocated to a Regular Shipper on the basis of its Base Shipment Percentage is greater than the quantity stated in its Nomination, the Regular Shipper will be allocated a portion of capacity that is equal to its Nomination, and the difference between the capacity allocation calculated on the basis of its Base Shipment Percentage and the quantity nominated will be reallocated among all other Regular Shippers having remaining unmet Nominations in proportion to their Base Shipment Percentages.
4. Any remaining Available Capacity not allocated through the application of subsections (2)-(3) above shall be allocated to all Shippers have remaining unmet Nominations in proportion to each Shipper’s unmet Nomination.
No Nominations shall be accepted beyond the amount that the nominating Shipper has readily accessible for shipment. To penalize inflation of Shippers’ Nominations, a Shipper’s capacity allocation for the next Proration Month will be reduced by the amount of allocated capacity not shipped by the Shipper in the immediately preceding Proration Month.
95. PUMPING CHARGE
For deliveries out of the Pipeline System terminal to connecting third-party terminals or pipelines at Cushing, when pumping services are provided by or on behalf of Carrier, [W] Uncommitted Shippers shall be assessed a charge of [D] $0.080 per barrel (or then-current market rate at Cushing) [N] and Committed Shippers shall be assessed a charge of $0.060 per barrel and will be paid by Shipper to the terminal operator. [N] These pumping charges shall be in addition to any connection fees that a connecting pipeline charges Carrier for such service (list available upon request).
[N] For deliveries out of the Pipeline System terminal to a tank or connecting pipeline at Ruby, there shall be no charge for pumping services when pumping services are provided by or on behalf of Carrier.
